{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775884719044,"sessionID":"ses_28506bbdeffedjQVhzWWbAvMbe","part":{"id":"prt_d7afa53c2001x8lyDsUvnzZaqe","messageID":"msg_d7afa48ea001lVmz2WAY7O943t","sessionID":"ses_28506bbdeffedjQVhzWWbAvMbe","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775884720291,"sessionID":"ses_28506bbdeffedjQVhzWWbAvMbe","part":{"id":"prt_d7afa55aa001xKM4HOUILUVv5q","messageID":"msg_d7afa48ea001lVmz2WAY7O943t","sessionID":"ses_28506bbdeffedjQVhzWWbAvMbe","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_613ce365813a46fead439384","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-039 — Go Unit Testing (router/store/picod)\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: This delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing Go unit tests for three core modules: router, store, and picod.\n6: \n7: ## Base Specifications\n8: \n9: - **AR**: AR-039\n10: - **Module**: `pkg`\n11: - **Language**: Go\n12: - **Size**: L\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## Background\n17: \n18: The agentcube project consists of three main modules requiring unit tests:\n19: \n20: 1. **pkg/router**: HTTP routing, proxy, health checking, rate limiting, authentication, session management, JWT\n21: 2. **pkg/store**: Valkey/Redis-backed session and sandbox storage\n22: 3. **pkg/picod**: Pico execution server with command execution and file handling\n23: \n24: ---\n25: \n26: ## Requirements\n27: \n28: ### Feature: Router Module - Initialization and Configuration\n29: \n30: #### Scenario: AR-039-001-A — Router creates with default config\n31: \n32: - **GIVEN** a nil config is passed to `NewRouter`\n33: - **WHEN** `NewRouter(config)` is called\n34: - **THEN** a Router instance is returned with default configuration values\n35: - **AND** default listen address is \":8080\"\n36: - **AND** backend timeout is 30 seconds\n37: - **AND** rate limiting is disabled by default\n38: \n39: #### Scenario: AR-039-001-B — Router creates with custom config\n40: \n41: - **GIVEN** a Config with SessionEnabled=true and JWTEnabled=true\n42: - **WHEN** `NewRouter(config)` is called\n43: - **THEN** a Router instance is returned with SessionManager initialized\n44: - **AND** JWTManager is initialized\n45: - **AND** SessionHandler is registered for /v1/sessions\n46: \n47: #### Scenario: AR-039-001-C — Router adds and removes backends\n48: \n49: - **GIVEN** a Router instance is created\n50: - **WHEN** `AddBackend(\"backend1\", \"http://localhost:8081\", \"/api\", \"backend-1\")` is called\n51: - **THEN** the backend is added to the pool\n52: - **WHEN** `RemoveBackend(\"backend1\")` is called\n53: - **THEN** the backend is removed from the pool\n54: \n55: ---\n56: \n57: ### Feature: Router Module - Backend Pool and Health Checking\n58: \n59: #### Scenario: AR-039-002-A — Backend pool routes requests\n60: \n61: - **GIVEN** a BackendPool with multiple backends registered\n62: - **WHEN** `GetBackendForRequest()` is called with a path matching a backend prefix\n63: - **THEN** the matching backend is returned\n64: - **WHEN** `GetBackendForRequest()` is called with a non-matching path\n65: - **THEN** nil is returned\n66: \n67: #### Scenario: AR-039-002-B — Health checker monitors backends\n68: \n69: - **GIVEN** a BackendPool with registered backends\n70: - **WHEN** HealthChecker Start() is invoked\n71: - **THEN** periodic health checks run at configured interval\n72: - **WHEN** a backend becomes unhealthy\n73: - **THEN** the backend is marked as unavailable\n74: - **WHEN** HealthChecker Stop() is invoked\n75: - **THEN** health checking stops\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: ### Feature: Router Module - Rate Limiting\n80: \n81: #### Scenario: AR-039-003-A — Rate limiter allows requests under limit\n82: \n83: - **GIVEN** RateLimiter with RPS=10 and Burst=20\n84: - **WHEN** 5 requests arrive in quick succession\n85: - **THEN** all requests are allowed through\n86: \n87: #### Scenario: AR-039-003-B — Rate limiter blocks requests over limit\n88: \n89: - **GIVEN** RateLimiter with RPS=2 and Burst=4\n90: - **WHEN** 10 requests arrive simultaneously\n91: - **THEN** requests beyond burst limit are blocked with 429 status\n92: \n93: #### Scenario: AR-039-003-C — Rate limiter can be disabled\n94: \n95: - **GIVEN** RateLimiter with enabled=false\n96: - **WHEN** any number of requests arrive\n97: - **THEN** all requests pass through without rate limiting\n98: \n99: ---\n100: \n101: ### Feature: Router Module - Authentication\n102: \n103: #### Scenario: AR-039-004-A — Authenticator validates token\n104: \n105: - **GIVEN** Authenticator with AuthEnabled=true and AuthToken=\"secret\"\n106: - **WHEN** request with \"Authorization: Bearer secret\" header arrives\n107: - **THEN** request is allowed\n108: - **WHEN** request with wrong token arrives\n109: - **THEN** request is rejected with 401 status\n110: \n111: #### Scenario: AR-039-004-B — Authenticator can be disabled\n112: \n113: - **GIVEN** Authenticator with AuthEnabled=false\n114: - **WHEN** any request arrives\n115: - **THEN** request passes through without token validation\n116: \n117: ---\n118: \n119: ### Feature: Router Module - Session Management\n120: \n121: #### Scenario: AR-039-005-A — Session manager creates session\n122: \n123: - **GIVEN** SessionManager with SessionEnabled=true\n124: - **WHEN** a new session is created via session store\n125: - **THEN** session ID is generated\n126: - **AND** session data is stored with expiry\n127: \n128: #### Scenario: AR-039-005-B — Session manager cleanup removes expired sessions\n129: \n130: - **GIVEN** SessionManager with sessions in store\n131: - **WHEN** cleanup runs and finds expired sessions\n132: - **THEN** expired sessions are removed from store\n133: \n134: #### Scenario: AR-039-005-C — Session middleware attaches session to request\n135: \n136: - **GIVEN** a request with valid session cookie\n137: - **WHEN** request passes through SessionMiddleware\n138: - **THEN** session info is available in request context\n139: \n140: ---\n141: \n142: ### Feature: Router Module - JWT Authentication\n143: \n144: #### Scenario: AR-039-006-A — JWT manager creates token\n145: \n146: - **GIVEN** JWTManager configured with HS256 algorithm and secret=\"mysecret\"\n147: - **WHEN** `GenerateToken(claims)` is called with user claims\n148: - **THEN** a signed JWT token is returned\n149: - **AND** token contains correct issuer and audience\n150: \n151: #### Scenario: AR-039-006-B — JWT manager validates token\n152: \n153: - **GIVEN** JWTManager configured with valid secret\n154: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called with a valid token\n155: - **THEN** claims are returned without error\n156: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called with an expired token\n157: - **THEN** error is returned indicating token expiration\n158: - **WHEN** `ValidateToken(token)` is called with invalid signature\n159: - **THEN** error is returned indicating invalid token\n160: \n161: #### Scenario: AR-039-006-C — JWT middleware enforces authentication\n162: \n163: - **GIVEN** JWTMiddleware with JWTEnabled=true and JWTAllowQueryParam=false\n164: - **WHEN** request without JWT arrives at protected endpoint\n165: - **THEN** request is rejected with 401 status\n166: - **WHEN** request with valid JWT in Authorization header arrives\n167: - **THEN** request is allowed and claims available in context\n168: - **WHEN** JWTAllowQueryParam=true and JWT in query param\n169: - **THEN** request is allowed\n170: \n171: ---\n172: \n173: ### Feature: Router Module - Logging and Metrics\n174: \n175: #### Scenario: AR-039-007-A — Logger records requests\n176: \n177: - **GIVEN** Logger middleware is in the chain\n178: - **WHEN** HTTP request arrives\n179: - **THEN** request details are logged including method, path, duration\n180: \n181: #### Scenario: AR-039-007-B — Metrics records request stats\n182: \n183: - **GIVEN** Metrics instance\n184: - **WHEN** `IncBackendRequests(backend, status)` is called\n185: - **THEN** backend request counter increments\n186: - **WHEN** `RecordRequestDuration(method, path, backend, duration)` is called\n187: - **THEN** request duration is recorded\n188: - **WHEN** `IncErrors(errorType)` is called\n189: - **THEN** error counter increments\n190: \n191: ---\n192: \n193: ### Feature: Store Module - Store Interface\n194: \n195: #### Scenario: AR-039-008-A — Store interface contract\n196: \n197: - **GIVEN** a Store implementation (Valkey or Redis)\n198: - **WHEN** all interface methods are called\n199: - **THEN** the Store implements the complete Store interface:\n200:   - Ping() error\n201:   - GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, sessionID) (*types.SandboxInfo, error)\n202:   - StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox) error\n203:   - UpdateSandbox(ctx, sandbox) error\n204:   - DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, sessionID) error\n205:   - ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit) ([]*types.SandboxInfo, error)\n206:   - ListInactiveSandboxes(ctx, before, limit) ([]*types.SandboxInfo, error)\n207:   - UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, sessionID, at) error\n208:   - Close() error\n209: \n210: ---\n211: \n212: ### Feature: Store Module - Valkey Store\n213: \n214: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-A — Valkey store connects with credentials\n215: \n216: - **GIVEN** environment variables VALKEY_ADDR and VALKEY_PASSWORD are set\n217: - **WHEN** `newValkeyStore()` is called\n218: - **THEN** a Valkey client connects successfully\n219: - **AND** ping returns \"PONG\"\n220: \n221: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-B — Valkey store requires address\n222: \n223: - **GIVEN** VALKEY_ADDR is not set\n224: - **WHEN** `newValkeyStore()` is called\n225: - **THEN** error is returned indicating VALKEY_ADDR is required\n226: \n227: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-C — Valkey store stores sandbox\n228: \n229: - **GIVEN** a valid SandboxInfo with SessionID and ExpiresAt\n230: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n231: - **THEN** sandbox is stored in Valkey\n232: - **AND** session is added to expiry index\n233: - **AND** session is added to last activity index\n234: \n235: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-D — Valkey store retrieves sandbox\n236: \n237: - **GIVEN** a sandbox was previously stored\n238: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, sessionID)` is called\n239: - **THEN** correct SandboxInfo is returned\n240: \n241: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-E — Valkey store returns error for non-existent session\n242: \n243: - **GIVEN** a session ID that doesn't exist\n244: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, sessionID)` is called\n245: - **THEN** ErrNotFound is returned\n246: \n247: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-F — Valkey store updates sandbox\n248: \n249: - **GIVEN** a sandbox exists in store\n250: - **WHEN** `UpdateSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n251: - **THEN** sandbox data is updated\n252: \n253: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-G — Valkey store deletes sandbox\n254: \n255: - **GIVEN** a sandbox exists in store\n256: - **WHEN** `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, sessionID)` is called\n257: - **THEN** sandbox is removed from store\n258: - **AND** session is removed from expiry index\n259: - **AND** session is removed from last activity index\n260: \n261: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-H — Valkey store lists expired sandboxes\n262: \n263: - **GIVEN** multiple sandboxes with different expiry times\n264: - **WHEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n265: - **THEN** only sandboxes expiring before 'before' are returned\n266: - **AND** maximum of 'limit' results are returned\n267: \n268: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-I — Valkey store lists inactive sandboxes\n269: \n270: - **GIVEN** multiple sandboxes with different last activity times\n271: - **WHEN** `ListInactiveSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n272: - **THEN** only sandboxes inactive before 'before' are returned\n273: - **AND** maximum of 'limit' results are returned\n274: \n275: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-J — Valkey store validates input\n276: \n277: - **GIVEN** nil sandbox passed to StoreSandbox\n278: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, nil)` is called\n279: - **THEN** error \"sandbox is nil\" is returned\n280: \n281: - **GIVEN** sandbox with zero ExpiresAt\n282: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n283: - **THEN** error \"invalid expiry: ExpiresAt is zero\" is returned\n284: \n285: - **GIVEN** sandbox with empty SessionID\n286: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n287: - **THEN** error \"session ID is required\" is returned\n288: \n289: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-K — Valkey store updates last activity\n290: \n291: - **GIVEN** a sandbox exists in store\n292: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, sessionID, time)` is called\n293: - **THEN** last activity timestamp is updated in index\n294: \n295: #### Scenario: AR-039-009-L — Valkey store closes connection\n296: \n297: - **GIVEN** a Valkey store is connected\n298: - **WHEN** `Close()` is called\n299: - **THEN** connection is closed\n300: \n301: ---\n302: \n303: ### Feature: Picod Module - Server Initialization\n304: \n305: #### Scenario: AR-039-010-A — Server creates with valid config\n306: \n307: - **GIVEN** valid Config and AuthConfig\n308: - **WHEN** `NewServer(config, authConfig)` is called\n309: - **THEN** server instance is returned\n310: - **AND** Gin engine is configured\n311: - **AND** routes are registered\n312: \n313: #### Scenario: AR-039-010-B — Server validates config\n314: \n315: - **GIVEN** Config with invalid values (e.g., negative port)\n316: - **WHEN** `NewServer(config, authConfig)` is called\n317: - **THEN** error is returned indicating invalid config\n318: \n319: #### Scenario: AR-039-010-C — Server sets workspace directory\n320: \n321: - **GIVEN** Config with Workspace=\"/tmp/test-workspace\"\n322: - **WHEN** Server initializes\n323: - **THEN** workspace directory is created if not exists\n324: \n325: #### Scenario: AR-039-010-D — Server creates with empty workspace\n326: \n327: - **GIVEN** Config with empty Workspace\n328: - **WHEN** Server initializes\n329: - **THEN** current working directory is used as workspace\n330: \n331: ---\n332: \n333: ### Feature: Picod Module - Path Sanitization\n334: \n335: #### Scenario: AR-039-011-A — Path sanitization allows safe paths\n336: \n337: - **GIVEN** Server with workspace=\"/app\"\n338: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath(\"subdir/file.txt\")` is called\n339: - **THEN** resolved path within workspace is returned\n340: \n341: #### Scenario: AR-039-011-B — Path sanitization blocks escape attempts\n342: \n343: - **GIVEN** Server with workspace=\"/app\"\n344: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath(\"../../../etc/passwd\")` is called\n345: - **THEN** error \"access denied: path escapes workspace\" is returned\n346: \n347: #### Scenario: AR-039-011-C — Path sanitization blocks absolute paths\n348: \n349: - **GIVEN** Server with workspace=\"/app\"\n350: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath(\"/etc/passwd\")` is called\n351: - **THEN** error \"access denied: path escapes workspace\" is returned\n352: \n353: #### Scenario: AR-039-011-D — Path sanitization handles symlinks\n354: \n355: - **GIVEN** Server with workspace=\"/app\" and symlink /app/link -> /tmp\n356: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath(\"link/sensitive\")` is called\n357: - **THEN** error \"access denied: path escapes workspace\" is returned\n358: \n359: ---\n360: \n361: ### Feature: Picod Module - Authentication\n362: \n363: #### Scenario: AR-039-012-A — Auth manager loads public key\n364: \n365: - **GIVEN** AuthConfig with valid RSA public key in PEM format\n366: - **WHEN** AuthManager initializes\n367: - **THEN** public key is loaded successfully\n368: \n369: #### Scenario: AR-039-012-B — Auth manager validates JWT\n370: \n371: - **GIVEN** AuthManager with loaded public key\n372: - **WHEN** valid JWT token is validated\n373: - **THEN** claims are returned\n374: \n375: #### Scenario: AR-039-012-C — Auth manager rejects invalid JWT\n376: \n377: - **GIVEN** AuthManager with loaded public key\n378: - **WHEN** invalid or expired JWT token is validated\n379: - **THEN** error is returned\n380: \n381: #### Scenario: AR-039-012-D — Auth middleware allows public paths\n382: \n383: - **GIVEN** request to public path like /health\n384: - **WHEN** request passes through auth middleware\n385: - **THEN** request is allowed without JWT validation\n386: \n387: #### Scenario: AR-039-012-E — Auth middleware requires auth for protected paths\n388: \n389: - **GIVEN** request to protected path /api/execute without token\n390: - **WHEN** request passes through auth middleware\n391: - **THEN** request is rejected with 401\n392: \n393: ---\n394: \n395: ### Feature: Picod Module - Execute Handler\n396: \n397: #### Scenario: AR-039-013-A — Execute handler runs valid command\n398: \n399: - **GIVEN** ExecuteRequest with Command=[\"echo\", \"hello\"]\n400: - **WHEN** ExecuteHandler processes request\n401: - **THEN** response with stdout=\"hello\", ExitCode=0 is returned\n402: \n403: #### Scenario: AR-039-013-B — Execute handler fails on empty command\n404: \n405: - **GIVEN** ExecuteRequest with empty Command array\n406: - **WHEN** ExecuteHandler processes request\n407: - **THEN** error response with code 400 is returned\n408: \n409: #### Scenario: AR-039-013-C — Execute handler respects timeout\n410: \n411: - **GIVEN** ExecuteRequest with Command=[\"sleep\", \"10\"] and Timeout=\"1s\"\n412: - **WHEN** ExecuteHandler processes request\n413: - **THEN** response with ExitCode=124 (timeout) is returned\n414: - **AND** stderr indicates timeout\n415: \n416: #### Scenario: AR-039-013-D — Execute handler validates working directory\n417: \n418: - **GIVEN** ExecuteRequest with WorkingDir=\"../../../etc\"\n419: - **WHEN** ExecuteHandler processes request\n420: - **THEN** error response with code 400 is returned\n421: \n422: #### Scenario: AR-039-013-E — Execute handler captures stderr\n423: \n424: - **GIVEN** ExecuteRequest with Command=[\"ls\", \"/nonexistent\"]\n425: - **WHEN** ExecuteHandler processes request\n426: - **THEN** response includes stderr output\n427: - **AND** non-zero ExitCode is returned\n428: \n429: #### Scenario: AR-039-013-F — Execute handler accepts custom environment\n430: \n431: - **GIVEN** ExecuteRequest with Command=[\"env\"] and Env={\"TEST_VAR\": \"test\"}\n432: - **WHEN** ExecuteHandler processes request\n433: - **THEN** response stdout contains TEST_VAR=test\n434: \n435: ---\n436: \n437: ### Feature: Picod Module - File Handlers\n438: \n439: #### Scenario: AR-039-014-A — Upload file handler saves file\n440: \n441: - **GIVEN** file upload request with valid content\n442: - **WHEN** UploadFileHandler processes request\n443: - **THEN** file is saved to workspace\n444: - **AND** success response is returned\n445: \n446: #### Scenario: AR-039-014-B — List files handler returns directory contents\n447: \n448: - **GIVEN** workspace with multiple files\n449: - **WHEN** ListFilesHandler is called\n450: - **THEN** list of files is returned\n451: \n452: #### Scenario: AR-039-014-C — Download file handler serves file\n453: \n454: - **GIVEN** file exists in workspace\n455: - **WHEN** DownloadFileHandler is called with path\n456: - **THEN** file content is served\n457: \n458: #### Scenario: AR-039-014-D — Download file handler blocks path escape\n459: \n460: - **GIVEN** request for file outside workspace\n461: - **WHEN** DownloadFileHandler processes request\n462: - **THEN** request is rejected\n463: \n464: ---\n465: \n466: ### Feature: Picod Module - Health Check and RSA Key Loading\n467: \n468: #### Scenario: AR-039-015-A — Health check returns healthy status\n469: \n470: - **GIVEN** Server is running\n471: - **WHEN** GET /health is requested\n472: - **THEN** response with status \"healthy\" is returned\n473: - **AND** HTTP 200 status code\n474: \n475: #### Scenario: AR-039-015-B — LoadRSAPublicKey parses valid PEM\n476: \n477: - **GIVEN** valid RSA public key in PEM format\n478: - **WHEN** `LoadRSAPublicKey(pemData)` is called\n479: - **THEN** *rsa.PublicKey is returned\n480: \n481: #### Scenario: AR-039-015-C — LoadRSAPublicKey rejects invalid PEM\n482: \n483: - **GIVEN** invalid PEM data\n484: - **WHEN** `LoadRSAPublicKey(pemData)` is called\n485: - **THEN** error is returned\n486: \n487: #### Scenario: AR-039-015-D — LoadRSAPublicKey rejects non-RSA key\n488: \n489: - **GIVEN** PEM data containing non-RSA key\n490: - **WHEN** `LoadRSAPublicKey(pemData)` is called\n491: - **THEN** error \"public key is not an RSA key\" is returned\n492: \n493: ---\n494: \n495: ## Acceptance Criteria\n496: \n497: ### Router Module\n498: - [ ] AC001: Unit tests for Config initialization and defaults\n499: - [ ] AC002: Unit tests for Router creation with various config combinations\n500: - [ ] AC003: Unit tests for BackendPool AddBackend, RemoveBackend, GetBackendForRequest\n501: - [ ] AC004: Unit tests for HealthChecker Start, Stop, checkBackend\n502: - [ ] AC005: Unit tests for RateLimiter Allow, Middleware\n503: - [ ] AC006: Unit tests for Authenticator Middleware with enabled/disabled states\n504: - [ ] AC007: Unit tests for SessionManager Create, Get, Delete, Cleanup\n505: - [ ] AC008: Unit tests for JWTManager GenerateToken, ValidateToken\n506: - [ ] AC009: Unit tests for JWTMiddleware with various configurations\n507: - [ ] AC010: Unit tests for Logger Middleware\n508: - [ ] AC011: Unit tests for Metrics IncBackendRequests, RecordRequestDuration, IncErrors\n509: \n510: ### Store Module\n511: - [ ] AC012: Unit tests for Valkey store connection with mocked client\n512: - [ ] AC013: Unit tests for StoreSandbox with valid and invalid inputs\n513: - [ ] AC014: Unit tests for GetSandboxBySessionID with existing and non-existing sessions\n514: - [ ] AC015: Unit tests for UpdateSandbox\n515: - [ ] AC016: Unit tests for DeleteSandboxBySessionID\n516: - [ ] AC017: Unit tests for ListExpiredSandboxes\n517: - [ ] AC018: Unit tests for ListInactiveSandboxes\n518: - [ ] AC019: Unit tests for UpdateSessionLastActivity\n519: - [ ] AC020: Unit tests for Close\n520: \n521: ### Picod Module\n522: - [ ] AC021: Unit tests for Server creation with valid and invalid configs\n523: - [ ] AC022: Unit tests for setWorkspace\n524: - [ ] AC023: Unit tests for sanitizePath with various path inputs\n525: - [ ] AC024: Unit tests for AuthManager LoadPublicKeyFromEnv, ValidateToken\n526: - [ ] AC025: Unit tests for auth middleware with public/protected paths\n527: - [ ] AC026: Unit tests for ExecuteHandler with valid commands, timeout, invalid working dir\n528: - [ ] AC027: Unit tests for UploadFileHandler, ListFilesHandler, DownloadFileHandler\n529: - [ ] AC028: Unit tests for HealthCheckHandler\n530: - [ ] AC029: Unit tests for LoadRSAPublicKey\n531: - [ ] AC030: Existing tests in router, store, picod packages remain passing\n532: \n533: ---\n534: \n535: ## Test File Status\n536: \n537: | Source File | Test File | Status |\n538: |-------------|-----------|--------|\n539: | router/server.go | server_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n540: | router/config.go | config_test.go | Complete |\n541: | router/route.go | route_test.go | Complete |\n542: | router/backend.go | backend_test.go | Complete |\n543: | router/health.go | health_test.go | Complete |\n544: | router/ratelimit.go | ratelimit_test.go | Complete |\n545: | router/auth.go | auth_test.go | Complete |\n546: | router/session.go | session_test.go | Complete |\n547: | router/jwt.go | jwt_test.go | Complete |\n548: | router/logging.go | logging_test.go | Complete |\n549: | router/metrics.go | (uses existing) | N/A |\n550: | store/store.go | (interface only) | N/A |\n551: | store/store_valkey.go | store_valkey_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n552: | store/store_redis.go | store_redis_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n553: | picod/server.go | server_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n554: | picod/execute.go | execute_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n555: | picod/auth.go | auth_test.go | Complete |\n556: | picod/files.go | files_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n557: | picod/health.go | health_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n558: \n559: ---\n560: \n561: ## Testing Patterns\n562: \n563: ### Mocking Strategy\n564: - Use interfaces for dependencies (Store, HTTP clients, etc.)\n565: - Create mock implementations for testing using testify/mock\n566: - Use gomock or testify.mock for generating mocks\n567: \n568: ### Test File Naming\n569: - Follow Go convention: `*_test.go`\n570: - Keep tests in same package as code under test\n571: - Use `package router` (not `package router_test`)\n572: \n573: ### Table-Driven Tests\n574: - Use table-driven tests for parameterized scenarios\n575: - Example pattern:\n576: ```go\n577: tests := []struct {\n578:     name    string\n579:     input   string\n580:     want    string\n581:     wantErr bool\n582: }{...}\n583: ```\n584: \n585: ### Test Coverage Goals\n586: - Router module: 70%+ code coverage\n587: - Store module: 80%+ code coverage\n588: - Picod module: 70%+ code coverage\n589: \n590: ---\n591: \n592: ## References\n593: \n594: - Router module: `pkg/router/`\n595: - Store module: `pkg/store/`\n596: - Picod module: `pkg/picod/`\n597: - Common types: `pkg/common/types/`\n598: \n599: ## Overview\n600: \n601: This delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing the CLI pack command in the AgentCube CLI tool (`kubectl-agentcube`).\n602: \n603: ## Base Specifications\n604: \n605: - **AR**: AR-020\n606: - **Module**: `cmd/cli`\n607: - **Language**: Python\n608: - **Size**: M\n609: \n610: ---\n611: \n612: ## Background\n613: \n614: The `pack` command is the first step in the AgentCube workflow. It validates the workspace structure, loads or creates agent metadata, processes dependencies, optionally generates a Dockerfile, and prepares the workspace for subsequent build and publish steps.\n615: \n616: ---\n617: \n618: ## Requirements\n619: \n620: ### AR-020-001: Workspace validation\n621: \n622: The system SHALL validate that the workspace path exists and contains valid agent source files based on the specified language.\n623: \n624: #### Scenario: AR-020-001-A — Valid Python workspace\n625: \n626: - **GIVEN** a workspace directory exists at the specified path\n627: - **WHEN** `pack` is executed with a Python agent (default language)\n628: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL validate that at least one `*.py` file exists in the workspace root\n629: - **AND** the workspace SHALL be considered valid for packaging\n630: \n631: #### Scenario: AR-020-001-B — Valid Java workspace\n632: \n633: - **GIVEN** a workspace directory exists at the specified path\n634: - **WHEN** `pack` is executed with `--language java`\n635: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL validate that `pom.xml` exists in the workspace root\n636: - **AND** the workspace SHALL be considered valid for packaging\n637: \n638: #### Scenario: AR-020-001-C — Missing workspace directory\n639: \n640: - **GIVEN** the specified workspace path does not exist or is not a directory\n641: - **WHEN** `PackRuntime._validate_workspace_structure` runs\n642: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` with message indicating the directory does not exist\n643: \n644: #### Scenario: AR-020-001-D — Python workspace without Python files\n645: \n646: - **GIVEN** `metadata.language` resolves to `\"python\"` (default)\n647: - **WHEN** no `*.py` file exists in the workspace root\n648: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError(\"No Python files found in workspace\")`\n649: \n650: #### Scenario: AR-020-001-E — Java workspace without pom.xml\n651: \n652: - **GIVEN** `metadata.language` is `\"java\"`\n653: - **WHEN** `pom.xml` does not exist in the workspace root\n654: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError(\"No pom.xml found in workspace\")`\n655: \n656: ---\n657: \n658: ### AR-020-002: Metadata loading and merging\n659: \n660: The system SHALL load existing agent metadata from the workspace and merge CLI option overrides to create a complete metadata configuration.\n661: \n662: #### Scenario: AR-020-002-A — Load existing metadata\n663: \n664: - **GIVEN** `agent_metadata.yaml` exists in the workspace\n665: - **WHEN** `PackRuntime._load_or_create_metadata` runs\n666: - **THEN** the system SHALL load the metadata using `MetadataService.load_metadata`\n667: - **AND** return an `AgentMetadata` object with all fields populated\n668: \n669: #### Scenario: AR-020-002-B — Fallback metadata file loading\n670: \n671: - **GIVEN** `agent_metadata.yaml` does NOT exist in the workspace\n672: - **WHEN** metadata loading is attempted\n673: - **THEN** the system SHALL attempt to load `agent.yaml`, then `metadata.yaml` as fallbacks\n674: - **AND** raise `FileNotFoundError` if none of the fallback files exist\n675: \n676: #### Scenario: AR-020-002-C — Create new metadata with defaults\n677: \n678: - **GIVEN** no metadata file exists in the workspace\n679: - **WHEN** `_load_or_create_metadata` runs\n680: - **THEN** the system SHALL create a new `AgentMetadata` with default values:\n681:   - `language`: `\"python\"`\n682:   - `port`: `8080`\n683:   - `build_mode`: `\"local\"`\n684:   - `requirements_file`: `\"requirements.txt\"`\n685: \n686: #### Scenario: AR-020-002-D — CLI option overrides\n687: \n688: - **GIVEN** existing metadata and CLI options are provided\n689: - **WHEN** `PackRuntime._apply_option_overrides` runs\n690: - **THEN** the system SHALL override metadata fields with CLI-provided values:\n691:   - `--agent-name` overrides `agent_name`\n692:   - `--language` overrides `language`\n693:   - `--entrypoint` overrides `entrypoint`\n694:   - `--port` overrides `port`\n695:   - `--build-mode` overrides `build_mode`\n696:   - `--description` overrides `description`\n697: \n698: ---\n699: \n700: ### AR-020-003: Dockerfile generation\n701: \n702: The system SHALL generate a Dockerfile in the workspace when packaging Python or Java agents.\n703: \n704: #### Scenario: AR-020-003-A — Generate Python Dockerfile\n705: \n706: - **GIVEN** `metadata.language` is `\"python\"` and no existing Dockerfile\n707: - **WHEN** `PackRuntime._generate_dockerfile` runs\n708: - **THEN** the system SHALL generate a Dockerfile using `_generate_python_dockerfile`\n709: - **AND** the Dockerfile SHALL include Python base image, dependency installation, entrypoint, and port exposure\n710: \n711: #### Scenario: AR-020-003-B — Generate Java Dockerfile\n712: \n713: - **GIVEN** `metadata.language` is `\"java\"` and no existing Dockerfile\n714: - **WHEN** `PackRuntime._generate_dockerfile` runs\n715: - **THEN** the system SHALL generate a Dockerfile using `_generate_java_dockerfile`\n716: - **AND** the Dockerfile SHALL include Maven/Java base image, dependency installation, entrypoint, and port exposure\n717: \n718: #### Scenario: AR-020-003-C — Skip Dockerfile when already exists\n719: \n720: - **GIVEN** a `Dockerfile` already exists in the workspace\n721: - **WHEN** `_generate_dockerfile` runs\n722: - **THEN** the system SHALL NOT overwrite the existing Dockerfile\n723: - **AND** return `None` indicating no new Dockerfile was generated\n724: \n725: ---\n726: \n727: ### AR-020-004: Dependency processing\n728: \n729: The system SHALL process agent dependencies based on the language.\n730: \n731: #### Scenario: AR-020-004-A — Process Python dependencies\n732: \n733: - **GIVEN** `requirements.txt` exists in a Python workspace\n734: - **WHEN** `_process_python_dependencies` runs\n735: - **THEN** the system SHALL validate the requirements file format\n736: \n737: #### Scenario: AR-020-004-B — Process Java dependencies\n738: \n739: - **GIVEN** `pom.xml` exists in a Java workspace\n740: - **WHEN** `_process_java_dependencies` runs\n741: - **THEN** the system SHALL validate the POM file exists\n742: \n743: #### Scenario: AR-020-004-C — Missing Python requirements file\n744: \n745: - **GIVEN** workspace language is Python but `requirements.txt` does not exist\n746: - **WHEN** `_process_python_dependencies` runs\n747: - **THEN** the system SHALL log a warning but continue (requirements are optional)\n748: \n749: ---\n750: \n751: ### AR-020-005: Output preparation\n752: \n753: The system SHALL prepare the output path for the packaged workspace.\n754: \n755: #### Scenario: AR-020-005-A — Default output path\n756: \n757: - **GIVEN** `--output` is not specified\n758: - **WHEN** `_prepare_output_path` runs\n759: - **THEN** the system SHALL use the original workspace path as the output\n760: \n761: #### Scenario: AR-020-005-B — Custom output path\n762: \n763: - **GIVEN** `--output` specifies a custom directory path\n764: - **WHEN** `_prepare_output_path` runs\n765: - **THEN** the system SHALL create the output directory if it does not exist\n766: \n767: #### Scenario: AR-020-005-C — Update metadata after packaging\n768: \n769: - **GIVEN** packaging completes successfully\n770: - **WHEN** `_update_pack_metadata` runs\n771: - **THEN** the system SHALL save the final `AgentMetadata` to `{output_path}/agent_metadata.yaml`\n772: \n773: ---\n774: \n775: ### AR-020-006: CLI interface\n776: \n777: The system SHALL expose the `pack` command via Typer with specific options.\n778: \n779: #### Scenario: AR-020-006-A — Pack command options\n780: \n781: - **GIVEN** the user runs `kubectl-agentcube pack --help`\n782: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL display:\n783:   - `-f, --workspace PATH` — Path to agent workspace (default: \".\")\n784:   - `--agent-name NAME` — Override agent name\n785:   - `--language LANG` — Programming language (python, java)\n786:   - `--entrypoint CMD` — Override entrypoint command\n787:   - `--port PORT` — Port to expose (default: 8080)\n788:   - `--build-mode MODE` — Build strategy (local, cloud)\n789:   - `--description TEXT` — Agent description\n790:   - `--output PATH` — Output path for packaged workspace\n791:   - `--verbose` — Enable detailed logging\n792: \n793: #### Scenario: AR-020-006-B — Successful pack output\n794: \n795: - **GIVEN** a valid workspace with all required files\n796: - **WHEN** `pack` completes without exception\n797: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL print success message using Rich `Progress` spinner\n798: - **AND** display agent name, resolved workspace path, and metadata file path\n799: \n800: #### Scenario: AR-020-006-C — Pack failure with verbose logging\n801: \n802: - **GIVEN** `PackRuntime.pack` raises an exception\n803: - **WHEN** `--verbose` flag is enabled\n804: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL print error message in red with full traceback\n805: - **AND** exit with code `1`\n806: \n807: #### Scenario: AR-020-006-D — Pack failure without verbose\n808: \n809: - **GIVEN** `PackRuntime.pack` raises an exception\n810: - **WHEN** `--verbose` flag is NOT enabled\n811: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL print error message in red without traceback\n812: - **AND** exit with code `1`\n813: \n814: ---\n815: \n816: ### AR-020-007: Language compatibility validation\n817: \n818: The system SHALL validate that the specified language and port are valid.\n819: \n820: #### Scenario: AR-020-007-A — Valid language specification\n821: \n822: - **GIVEN** `--language` is provided as `\"python\"` or `\"java\"` (case-insensitive)\n823: - **WHEN** `_validate_language_compatibility` runs\n824: - **THEN** the validation SHALL pass successfully\n825: \n826: #### Scenario: AR-020-007-B — Invalid language specification\n827: \n828: - **GIVEN** `--language` is provided as an unsupported value\n829: - **WHEN** Pydantic validator runs on the metadata\n830: - **THEN** validation SHALL fail with `ValueError` indicating valid options are `python` or `java`\n831: \n832: #### Scenario: AR-020-007-C — Port range validation\n833: \n834: - **GIVEN** `--port` is provided with a value outside valid range\n835: - **WHEN** Pydantic validator runs on the metadata\n836: - **THEN** validation SHALL fail with `ValueError` indicating port must be between 1 and 65535\n837: \n838: ---\n839: \n840: ### AR-020-008: Entrypoint inference\n841: \n842: The system SHALL infer the entrypoint command if not explicitly provided.\n843: \n844: #### Scenario: AR-020-008-A — Infer Python entrypoint\n845: \n846: - **GIVEN** `--entrypoint` is not provided for a Python agent\n847: - **WHEN** `_infer_entrypoint` runs\n848: - **THEN** the system SHALL look for `main.py` in the workspace root\n849: - **AND** default to `python main.py` if found\n850: \n851: #### Scenario: AR-020-008-B — Infer Java entrypoint\n852: \n853: - **GIVEN** `--entrypoint` is not provided for a Java agent\n854: - **WHEN** `_infer_entrypoint` runs\n855: - **THEN** the system SHALL look for a main class in `pom.xml`\n856: - **AND** default to `java -jar target/*.jar` if a JAR is expected\n857: \n858: ---\n859: \n860: ## Acceptance Criteria\n861: \n862: - [ ] AC001: Pack validates workspace structure before processing\n863: - [ ] AC002: Pack loads or creates metadata with proper defaults\n864: - [ ] AC003: Pack merges CLI option overrides into metadata\n865: - [ ] AC004: Pack generates Dockerfile when needed (Python/Java)\n866: - [ ] AC005: Pack processes dependencies for the target language\n867: - [ ] AC006: Pack prepares output path and saves metadata\n868: - [ ] AC007: Pack displays success output with Rich formatting\n869: - [ ] AC008: Pack handles errors with proper exit codes and verbose logging\n870: - [ ] AC009: Pack validates language and port values\n871: - [ ] AC010: Pack infers entrypoint when not provided\n872: \n873: ---\n874: \n875: ## Architecture Notes\n876: \n877: ### Key Components\n878: \n879: | Component | Path | Description |\n880: |-----------|------|-------------|\n881: | CLI Entry | `agentcube/cli/main.py` | Typer app with `pack` command |\n882: | PackRuntime | `agentcube/runtime/pack_runtime.py` | Core packaging logic |\n883: | MetadataService | `agentcube/services/metadata_service.py` | Metadata CRUD operations |\n884: | AgentMetadata | `agentcube/services/metadata_service.py` | Pydantic model for agent config |\n885: | DockerService | `agentcube/services/docker_service.py` | Dockerfile generation and Docker operations |\n886: \n887: ### Metadata Fields (AgentMetadata)\n888: \n889: | Field | Type | Default | Description |\n890: |-------|------|---------|-------------|\n891: | agent_name | str | (required) | Unique name identifying the agent |\n892: | language | str | \"python\" | Programming language used |\n893: | entrypoint | str | (required) | Command to launch the agent |\n894: | port | int | 8080 | Port exposed by the agent runtime |\n895: | build_mode | str | \"local\" | Build strategy: local or cloud |\n896: | description | Optional[str] | None | Human-readable summary |\n897: | requirements_file | Optional[str] | \"requirements.txt\" | Python dependency file |\n898: \n899: ### CLI Options Mapping\n900: \n901: | CLI Option | Metadata Field | Type |\n902: |------------|----------------|------|\n903: | `--agent-name` | agent_name | Optional[str] |\n904: | `--language` | language | Optional[str] |\n905: | `--entrypoint` | entrypoint | Optional[str] |\n906: | `--port` | port | Optional[int] |\n907: | `--build-mode` | build_mode | Optional[str] |\n908: | `--description` | description | Optional[str] |\n909: | `--output` | (output path) | Optional[str] |\n910: \n911: ---\n912: \n913: # Delta Spec: AR-038 — Go Unit Testing (workloadmanager)\n914: \n915: ## Overview\n916: \n917: This delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing Go unit tests for the workloadmanager module (`pkg/workloadmanager`).\n918: \n919: ## Base Specifications\n920: \n921: - **AR**: AR-038\n922: - **Module**: `pkg/workloadmanager`\n923: - **Language**: Go\n924: - **Size**: L\n925: \n926: ## Reference\n927: \n928: Base spec: client-go library from `/tmp/agentcube-ref/client-go/`\n929: \n930: ---\n931: \n932: ## Background\n933: \n934: The workloadmanager module provides workload management for AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources in Kubernetes. It includes:\n935: - WorkloadManager interface for CRUD operations\n936: - GC (Garbage Collection) worker for expired resource cleanup\n937: - Expiration checker for TTL and idle timeout\n938: - Graceful manager for connection draining\n939: - Cleanup manager for orphaned resources\n940: - Batch manager for bulk operations\n941: - HTTP server with REST API endpoints\n942: \n943: ---\n944: \n945: ## Requirements\n946: \n947: ### Feature: CleanupManager Resource Cleanup\n948: \n949: #### Scenario: AR-038-001-A — CleanupManager deletes orphaned services\n950: \n951: - **GIVEN** a CleanupManager with a Kubernetes client\n952: - **WHEN** cleanupServices is called with a namespace and owner reference\n953: - **THEN** it should return a list of cleaned service resource strings\n954: - **AND** services with matching owner references should be deleted\n955: \n956: #### Scenario: AR-038-001-B — CleanupManager deletes orphaned configmaps\n957: \n958: - **GIVEN** a CleanupManager with a Kubernetes client\n959: - **WHEN** cleanupConfigMaps is called with a namespace and owner reference\n960: - **THEN** it should return a list of cleaned configmap resource strings\n961: - **AND** configmaps with the annotation `agentcube.volcano.sh/auto-delete=true` and matching owner should be deleted\n962: \n963: #### Scenario: AR-038-001-C — CleanupManager handles retained PVCs\n964: \n965: - **GIVEN** a CleanupManager with a Kubernetes client\n966: - **WHEN** cleanupPVCs is called with a namespace and owner reference for a PVC with Retain policy\n967: - **THEN** the PVC should not be deleted\n968: - **AND** other PVCs with matching owner should be deleted\n969: \n970: #### Scenario: AR-038-001-D — CleanupManager cleans orphaned resources\n971: \n972: - **GIVEN** a CleanupManager and a Sandbox object\n973: - **WHEN** cleanupOrphanedResources is called\n974: - **THEN** it should clean services, configmaps, and PVCs associated with the sandbox\n975: \n976: #### Scenario: AR-038-001-E — CleanupManager finds orphaned services\n977: \n978: - **GIVEN** a CleanupManager with a Kubernetes client\n979: - **WHEN** FindOrphanedServices is called with namespace and sessionID\n980: - **THEN** it should return service names that have no owner references\n981: \n982: #### Scenario: AR-038-001-F — CleanupManager CleanupAllResources\n983: \n984: - **GIVEN** a CleanupManager with a Kubernetes client\n985: - **WHEN** CleanupAllResources is called with a sandbox\n986: - **THEN** it should clean all associated resources\n987: \n988: ---\n989: \n990: ### Feature: BatchManager Operations\n991: \n992: #### Scenario: AR-038-002-A — BatchManager deletes all sandboxes synchronously under threshold\n993: \n994: - **GIVEN** a BatchManager with workloadMgr and gracefulMgr\n995: - **WHEN** handleDeleteAllSandboxes is called with fewer than AsyncThreshold (10) sandboxes\n996: - **THEN** it should delete all sandboxes synchronously\n997: - **AND** return a BatchDeleteResponse with deleted and failed counts\n998: \n999: #### Scenario: AR-038-002-B — BatchManager deletes all sandboxes asynchronously over threshold\n1000: \n1001: - **GIVEN** a BatchManager with workloadMgr and gracefulMgr\n1002: - **WHEN** handleDeleteAllSandboxes is called with more than AsyncThreshold (10) sandboxes\n1003: - **THEN** it should start async deletion in background\n1004: - **AND** return immediately with all items marked as deleted\n1005: \n1006: #### Scenario: AR-038-002-C — BatchManager deletes stale sandboxes\n1007: \n1008: - **GIVEN** a BatchManager with workloadMgr and gracefulMgr\n1009: - **WHEN** deleteStaleSandboxes is called\n1010: - **THEN** it should delete all sandboxes in Unknown or Failed state older than StaleStateThreshold (1 hour)\n1011: - **AND** return a BatchDeleteResponse with results\n1012: \n1013: #### Scenario: AR-038-002-D — BatchManager deletes by label selector\n1014: \n1015: - **GIVEN** a BatchManager with workloadMgr and gracefulMgr\n1016: - **WHEN** handleDeleteByLabelSelector is called with a label selector\n1017: - **THEN** it should delete all sandboxes matching the label selector\n1018: \n1019: #### Scenario: AR-038-002-E — BatchManager public methods\n1020: \n1021: - **GIVEN** a BatchManager\n1022: - **WHEN** DeleteAllInNamespace, DeleteByLabelSelector, or DeleteStaleSandboxes are called\n1023: - **THEN** they should delegate to the appropriate handler methods\n1024: \n1025: ---\n1026: \n1027: ### Feature: WorkloadManager Sandbox Operations\n1028: \n1029: #### Scenario: AR-038-003-A — GetSandboxBySessionID finds AgentRuntime\n1030: \n1031: - **GIVEN** a WorkloadManager with a client that has AgentRuntime resources\n1032: - **WHEN** GetSandboxBySessionID is called with a sessionID that exists in an AgentRuntime\n1033: - **THEN** it should return a Sandbox object with correct fields\n1034: \n1035: #### Scenario: AR-038-003-B — GetSandboxBySessionID finds CodeInterpreter\n1036: \n1037: - **GIVEN** a WorkloadManager with a client that has CodeInterpreter resources\n1038: - **WHEN** GetSandboxBySessionID is called with a sessionID that exists in a CodeInterpreter\n1039: - **THEN** it should return a Sandbox object with correct fields\n1040: \n1041: #### Scenario: AR-038-003-C — GetSandboxBySessionID returns error when not found\n1042: \n1043: - **GIVEN** a WorkloadManager with a client\n1044: - **WHEN** GetSandboxBySessionID is called with a non-existent sessionID\n1045: - **THEN** it should return ErrSandboxNotFound\n1046: \n1047: #### Scenario: AR-038-003-D — DeleteSandbox deletes AgentRuntime by sessionId\n1048: \n1049: - **GIVEN** a WorkloadManager with a client that has AgentRuntime with matching sessionId label\n1050: - **WHEN** DeleteSandbox is called with namespace, sessionID, and delete options\n1051: - **THEN** it should delete the matching AgentRuntime\n1052: - **AND** return nil on success\n1053: \n1054: #### Scenario: AR-038-003-E — DeleteSandbox deletes CodeInterpreter by sessionId\n1055: \n1056: - **GIVEN** a WorkloadManager with a client that has CodeInterpreter with matching sessionId label\n1057: - **WHEN** DeleteSandbox is called with namespace, sessionID, and delete options\n1058: - **THEN** it should delete the matching CodeInterpreter\n1059: - **AND** return nil on success\n1060: \n1061: #### Scenario: AR-038-003-F — DeleteSandbox applies force delete\n1062: \n1063: - **GIVEN** a WorkloadManager with a client\n1064: - **WHEN** DeleteSandbox is called with Force=true\n1065: - **THEN** it should set GracePeriodSeconds to 0\n1066: \n1067: #### Scenario: AR-038-003-G — DeleteSandbox applies label selector\n1068: \n1069: - **GIVEN** a WorkloadManager with a client\n1070: - **WHEN** DeleteSandbox is called with LabelSelector\n1071: - **THEN** it should use the label selector when listing resources\n1072: \n1073: #### Scenario: AR-038-003-H — ListSandboxes returns combined list\n1074: \n1075: - **GIVEN** a WorkloadManager with a client that has both AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources\n1076: - **WHEN** ListSandboxes is called with namespace and ListOptions\n1077: - **THEN** it should return a SandboxList containing both types\n1078: - **AND** apply label and field selectors correctly\n1079: \n1080: ---\n1081: \n1082: ### Feature: Server HTTP Handlers\n1083: \n1084: #### Scenario: AR-038-004-A — Server health check endpoint\n1085: \n1086: - **GIVEN** a Server instance\n1087: - **WHEN** GET /healthz is requested\n1088: - **THEN** it should return HTTP 200 with \"ok\"\n1089: \n1090: #### Scenario: AR-038-004-B — Server readiness check - ready\n1091: \n1092: - **GIVEN** a Server with ready=true\n1093: - **WHEN** GET /readyz is requested\n1094: - **THEN** it should return HTTP 200 with status \"ok\"\n1095: \n1096: #### Scenario: AR-038-004-C — Server readiness check - not ready\n1097: \n1098: - **GIVEN** a Server with ready=false\n1099: - **WHEN** GET /readyz is requested\n1100: - **THEN** it should return HTTP 503 with status \"not ready\"\n1101: \n1102: #### Scenario: AR-038-004-D — Server starts and stops cleanly\n1103: \n1104: - **GIVEN** a Server with valid config\n1105: - **WHEN** Start() is called\n1106: - **THEN** it should bind to the configured port\n1107: - **AND** Start() should return nil\n1108: \n1109: #### Scenario: AR-038-004-E — Server handles API error mapping\n1110: \n1111: - **GIVEN** a Server with a WorkloadManager that returns an error\n1112: - **WHEN** handleError is called with k8s IsNotFound error\n1113: - **THEN** it should return HTTP 404 with reason \"NotFound\"\n1114: \n1115: #### Scenario: AR-038-004-F — Server corsMiddleware sets headers\n1116: \n1117: - **GIVEN** a Server\n1118: - **WHEN** corsMiddleware processes a request\n1119: - **THEN** it should set Access-Control-Allow-* headers\n1120: - **AND** handle OPTIONS preflight requests\n1121: \n1122: ---\n1123: \n1124: ### Feature: GracefulManager Operations\n1125: \n1126: #### Scenario: AR-038-005-A — GracefulManager registers connection\n1127: \n1128: - **GIVEN** a GracefulManager\n1129: - **WHEN** RegisterConnection is called with a sandboxID\n1130: - **THEN** the active connection count should increment\n1131: \n1132: #### Scenario: AR-038-005-B — GracefulManager unregisters connection\n1133: \n1134: - **GIVEN** a GracefulManager with an active connection\n1135: - **WHEN** UnregisterConnection is called with the sandboxID\n1136: - **THEN** the active connection count should decrement\n1137: \n1138: #### Scenario: AR-038-005-C — GracefulManager drains connections\n1139: \n1140: - **GIVEN** a GracefulManager\n1141: - **WHEN** drainConnections is called with a sandboxID\n1142: - **THEN** the draining flag should be set to true\n1143: \n1144: #### Scenario: AR-038-005-D — GracefulManager checks if draining\n1145: \n1146: - **GIVEN** a GracefulManager with a sandbox marked for draining\n1147: - **WHEN** IsDraining is called with the sandboxID\n1148: - **THEN** it should return true\n1149: \n1150: #### Scenario: AR-038-005-E — GracefulManager gets active connections\n1151: \n1152: - **GIVEN** a GracefulManager with registered connections\n1153: - **WHEN** GetActiveConnections is called\n1154: - **THEN** it should return the correct count\n1155: \n1156: #### Scenario: AR-038-005-F — GracefulManager cleans up sandbox state\n1157: \n1158: - **GIVEN** a GracefulManager with a sandbox\n1159: - **WHEN** Cleanup is called with the sandboxID\n1160: - **THEN** the sandbox entry should be removed from connections map\n1161: \n1162: #### Scenario: AR-038-005-G — GracefulManager waitForConnections timeout\n1163: \n1164: - **GIVEN** a GracefulManager with active connections that never drain\n1165: - **WHEN** waitForConnections is called with a short timeout\n1166: - **THEN** it should return an error after timeout\n1167: \n1168: ---\n1169: \n1170: ### Feature: K8sClient Initialization\n1171: \n1172: #### Scenario: AR-038-006-A — K8sClient NewK8sClient with kubeconfig path\n1173: \n1174: - **GIVEN** a valid kubeconfig path\n1175: - **WHEN** NewK8sClient is called with the path\n1176: - **THEN** it should return a K8sClient with Clientset, KubernetesClient, and DynamicClient\n1177: - **AND** return nil error\n1178: \n1179: #### Scenario: AR-038-006-B — K8sClient NewK8sClient with in-cluster mode\n1180: \n1181: - **GIVEN** InClusterMode constant\n1182: - **WHEN** NewK8sClient is called with InClusterMode\n1183: - **THEN** it should attempt in-cluster config\n1184: \n1185: #### Scenario: AR-038-006-C — K8sClient NewInClusterClient\n1186: \n1187: - **GIVEN** running inside a Kubernetes cluster\n1188: - **WHEN** NewInClusterClient is called\n1189: - **THEN** it should create clients using in-cluster config\n1190: \n1191: #### Scenario: AR-038-006-D — K8sClient expandKubeconfigPath handles tilde\n1192: \n1193: - **GIVEN** a path starting with ~\n1194: - **WHEN** expandKubeconfigPath is called\n1195: - **THEN** it should replace ~ with the home directory\n1196: \n1197: #### Scenario: AR-038-006-E — K8sClient expandKubeconfigPath handles empty path\n1198: \n1199: - **GIVEN** an empty string\n1200: - **WHEN** expandKubeconfigPath is called\n1201: - **THEN** it should return the empty string\n1202: \n1203: ---\n1204: \n1205: ### Feature: Type Helper Functions\n1206: \n1207: #### Scenario: AR-038-007-A — NewAPIResponse creates correct response\n1208: \n1209: - **GIVEN** data and metadata\n1210: - **WHEN** NewAPIResponse is called\n1211: - **THEN** it should return an APIResponse with Status=\"Success\"\n1212: \n1213: #### Scenario: AR-038-007-B — NewAPIError creates correct error\n1214: \n1215: - **GIVEN** message, reason, and code\n1216: - **WHEN** NewAPIError is called\n1217: - **THEN** it should return an APIError with Status=\"Failure\"\n1218: \n1219: #### Scenario: AR-038-007-C — sandboxFromAgentRuntime maps running state\n1220: \n1221: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime with Running condition\n1222: - **WHEN** sandboxFromAgentRuntime is called\n1223: - **THEN** the returned Sandbox should have State=SandboxStateRunning\n1224: \n1225: #### Scenario: AR-038-007-D — sandboxFromAgentRuntime maps failed state\n1226: \n1227: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime with Failed condition\n1228: - **WHEN** sandboxFromAgentRuntime is called\n1229: - **THEN** the returned Sandbox should have State=SandboxStateFailed\n1230: \n1231: #### Scenario: AR-038-007-E — sandboxFromAgentRuntime maps deleting state\n1232: \n1233: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime with DeletionTimestamp\n1234: - **WHEN** sandboxFromAgentRuntime is called\n1235: - **THEN** the returned Sandbox should have State=SandboxStateDeleting\n1236: \n1237: #### Scenario: AR-038-007-F — sandboxFromCodeInterpreter maps running state\n1238: \n1239: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter with Ready=true\n1240: - **WHEN** sandboxFromCodeInterpreter is called\n1241: - **THEN** the returned Sandbox should have State=SandboxStateRunning\n1242: \n1243: ---\n1244: \n1245: ### Feature: ListExpiredSandboxes\n1246: \n1247: #### Scenario: AR-038-008-A — ListExpiredSandboxes returns expired AgentRuntimes\n1248: \n1249: - **GIVEN** a client with AgentRuntime resources\n1250: - **WHEN** ListExpiredSandboxes is called\n1251: - **THEN** it should return sandboxes that have expired\n1252: \n1253: #### Scenario: AR-038-008-B — ListExpiredSandboxes returns expired CodeInterpreters\n1254: \n1255: - **GIVEN** a client with CodeInterpreter resources\n1256: - **WHEN** ListExpiredSandboxes is called\n1257: - **THEN** it should return sandboxes that have expired\n1258: \n1259: #### Scenario: AR-038-008-C — ListExpiredSandboxes handles empty namespace\n1260: \n1261: - **GIVEN** a client with resources in a namespace\n1262: - **WHEN** ListExpiredSandboxes is called with an empty namespace string\n1263: - **THEN** it should list all expired sandboxes\n1264: \n1265: ---\n1266: \n1267: ### Feature: Retry Logic\n1268: \n1269: #### Scenario: AR-038-009-A — Retry with exponential backoff\n1270: \n1271: - **GIVEN** a function that fails initially then succeeds\n1272: - **WHEN** retry logic is applied\n1273: - **THEN** it should retry with increasing delays\n1274: - **AND** ultimately succeed\n1275: \n1276: #### Scenario: AR-038-009-B — Retry stops after max attempts\n1277: \n1278: - **GIVEN** a function that always fails\n1279: - **WHEN** retry logic is applied with max attempts\n1280: - **THEN** it should return the last error after exhausting retries\n1281: \n1282: ---\n1283: \n1284: ## Acceptance Criteria\n1285: \n1286: - [ ] AC001: All CleanupManager methods must have unit tests covering success and error paths\n1287: - [ ] AC002: All BatchManager methods must have tests with mocked WorkloadManager\n1288: - [ ] AC003: WorkloadManager sandbox operations must have tests with fake clients\n1289: - [ ] AC004: Server HTTP handlers must have tests using httptest\n1290: - [ ] AC005: GracefulManager connection tracking must have unit tests\n1291: - [ ] AC006: K8sClient initialization must have tests for different config modes\n1292: - [ ] AC007: Helper functions (NewAPIResponse, NewAPIError, sandboxFrom*) must have tests\n1293: - [ ] AC008: ListExpiredSandboxes must have tests for both resource types\n1294: - [ ] AC009: Retry logic must have unit tests for backoff behavior\n1295: - [ ] AC010: Existing tests in service_test.go, gc_test.go, expiration_test.go remain passing\n1296: \n1297: ---\n1298: \n1299: ## Test File Status\n1300: \n1301: | Source File | Test File | Status |\n1302: |-------------|-----------|--------|\n1303: | service.go | service_test.go | Complete |\n1304: | gc.go | gc_test.go | Complete |\n1305: | expiration.go | expiration_test.go | Complete |\n1306: | cleanup.go | cleanup_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n1307: | server.go | server_test.go | Complete |\n1308: | graceful.go | graceful_test.go | Complete |\n1309: | batch.go | batch_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n1310: | client.go | client_test.go | Complete |\n1311: | delete_test.go | N/A | Exists |\n1312: | retry.go | retry_test.go | **Missing - Needs Implementation** |\n1313: \n1314: ---\n1315: \n1316: ## References\n1317: \n1318: - Client-go library: `/tmp/agentcube-ref/client-go/`\n1319: - API Group: `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh / v1alpha1`\n1320: - Resources: AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter\n\n(End of file - total 1320 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-039 — Go Unit Testing (router/store/picod)\n\n## Overview\n\nThis delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing Go unit tests for three core modules: router, store, and picod.\n\n## Base Specifications\n\n- **AR**: AR-039\n- **Module**: `pkg`\n- **Language**: Go\n- **Size**: L\n\n---\n\n## Background\n\nThe agentcube project consists of three main modules requiring unit tests:\n\n1. **pkg/router**: HTTP routing, proxy, health checking, rate limiting, authentication, session management, JWT","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775884720274,"end":1775884720285}}}}
